One example: it occupies a normal

00:09:13.820 --> 00:09:17.490
lattice site. So,
there is the dopant that we've seen

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:21.160
before. And, I'll show you towards
the end of the lecture,

00:09:21.160 --> 00:09:24.870
boron in diamond.
Substitutional,

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:28.620
it actually sits at the normal
carbon lattice site.

00:09:28.620 --> 00:09:32.370
They are also alloying elements
such as magnesium in aluminum.

00:09:32.370 --> 00:09:36.120
There are very few metals that are
used in commerce in pure form.

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:39.870
Most metals are used in the form of
alloys, that is to say solid

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:43.620
solutions. So,
for example, this aluminum can is

00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:47.370
dominantly aluminum and contains a
certain amount of magnesium and a

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:51.120
certain amount of silicon.
And, this is designed to give it

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:55.070
the properties it needs.
One of the main properties that we

00:09:55.070 --> 00:09:59.210
need in this can stock is the
ability to have very,

00:09:59.210 --> 00:10:03.350
very rapid glide of the atoms.
If you look very carefully, there's

00:10:03.350 --> 00:10:07.490
no seam on the bottom of this can.
This is made out of a single sheet

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:11.640
of aluminum. And so,
the sheet moves over a dye,

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:15.780
press punches down, up, down,
and forms the U-shaped right

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:19.920
circular cylinder,
and then a second piece is crimped

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:23.620
onto the top.
You can imagine the high speed at

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:26.870
which the atoms are gliding over one
another, and part of what gives us

00:10:26.870 --> 00:10:30.120
the ability to deform is the
alloying. So,

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:33.370
magnesium is purposely added to
aluminum. We have seen colored

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:36.620
golds. And, one example is nickel
going into gold,

00:10:36.620 --> 00:10:39.870
which will turn it from its very
buttery, almost buttery ductility

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:43.120
into something that's got a little
bit of strength to it.

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:46.370
I mean, you don't want a ring that
if you put it down on the dresser it

00:10:46.370 --> 00:10:49.880
starts to deform.
So, we have to give it some strength.

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:53.660
And, in this case,
we can alter its color.

00:10:53.660 --> 00:10:57.440
So, this is nickel atom sitting on
the FCC site normally occupied by

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:01.220
gold, again, a substitutional
impurity. And,

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:04.990
here's the last one.
We learned about 7-Up,

00:11:04.990 --> 00:11:08.770
and the lithium citrate in 7-Up,
suppose you're on call and you're

00:11:08.770 --> 00:11:12.550
administering saline in the hospital,
and it's supposed to be 5% sodium

00:11:12.550 --> 00:11:16.330
chloride in water.
But if there's a lithium impurity

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:20.110
substituting for sodium in the
sodium chloride lattice,

00:11:20.110 --> 00:11:23.750
it's going to dissolve.
And if you've got some sodium

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:27.250
deficient patient and you give them
some lithium chloride,

00:11:27.250 --> 00:11:30.750
it's going to be a bad day at the
office. So, substitutional

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:34.250
impurities can have deleterious
effects. So, those are examples of

00:11:34.250 --> 00:11:37.750
substitutional impurities.
The second type is the interstitial

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:41.250
impurity. And,
it occupies the position between the

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:44.750
lattice sites.
And, if you go to the cartoon,

00:11:44.750 --> 00:11:48.250
you'll see this highlighted. And,
the interstitial impurity, obviously

00:11:48.250 --> 00:12:07.466
this atom is small.
It has to fit into the void space

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:37.500
between the atoms.
So, we did the calculations.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:42.500
We know that a close packed FCC
lattice is 74% matter,

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:47.500
and 26% void. Well, that 26% void
is not just randomly distributed.

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:52.500
It is the nothing in between the
atoms. So, I could take all the

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:57.500
atoms away, and I could give you a
lattice comprising the

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:21.660
interstitial sites.
You understand the concept.

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:24.990
A lattice is simply points in space.
So, instead of putting gold atoms

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:28.330
there, let's put the space between
the gold atoms.

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:31.660
And, imagine what we can do.
So, here's an example of an

00:12:31.660 --> 00:12:34.990
interstitial atom.
It's small, and it's obviously an

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:38.330
impurity because it's different from
the composition of the parent

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:41.660
material. And,
so, there are desirable and

00:12:41.660 --> 00:12:44.990
undesirable. So,
an example of a desirable element is

00:12:44.990 --> 00:12:48.330
carbon in iron.
Carbon in iron is the basis for

00:12:48.330 --> 00:12:52.720
steel.
Without carbon and iron,

00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:58.180
we wouldn't have steel. And,
the interesting thing about carbon

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:03.630
in iron is that the radius of the
carbon atom is actually greater than

00:13:03.630 --> 00:13:09.080
the radius of the interstitial site
in iron, greater than the radius of

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:14.540
the interstitial site in iron.
So, therefore, when the carbon goes

00:13:14.540 --> 00:13:33.146
into that interstitial site,
it actually distorts the lattice.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:24.260
It presses back on the parent iron
lattice. And,

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:28.530
through this distortion,
strengthens the material.

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:32.790
Another example is hydrogen in
lanthanum nickel five.

00:13:32.790 --> 00:13:37.060
It goes into the interstices in
this compound.

00:13:37.060 --> 00:13:41.330
Lanthanum nickel five has voids
that are large enough to accommodate

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:45.590
hydrogen. And,
hydrogen can go in this,

00:13:45.590 --> 00:13:49.860
acts as a sponge, and hydrogen at
peak loading can go

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:53.550
in at this level.
We have a huge amount of hydrogen

00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:56.660
going in here.
The density of hydrogen in

00:13:56.660 --> 00:13:59.770
lanthanum nickel five at saturation
is greater than liquid hydrogen

00:13:59.770 --> 00:14:02.880
itself. And, this material is under
investigation along with others like

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:05.990
it in the context of hydrogen
powered vehicles.

00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:09.100
If we're going to put hydrogen in
cars, if at some point fuel cells

00:14:09.100 --> 00:14:12.220
become practical,
what is going to be the mode of

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:15.330
storing hydrogen?
Do we want compressed hydrogen?

00:14:15.330 --> 00:14:18.440
We're going to have to have all
sorts of protection in

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:21.880
case of a collision.
Well, this might be a safer way of

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:25.660
putting hydrogen in the vehicle.
So, interstitial packing is

00:14:25.660 --> 00:14:29.440
advantageous in this case.
But, if we get our wires crossed,

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:33.220
and instead of putting hydrogen in
lanthanum nickel five,

00:14:33.220 --> 00:14:36.990
we put hydrogen in iron,
that leads to deleterious effects.

00:14:36.990 --> 00:14:40.770
Hydrogen in iron embrittles iron.
And it loses its ductility,

00:14:40.770 --> 00:14:44.550
becomes very brittle, and can fail
prematurely. And this is also

00:14:44.550 --> 00:14:48.330
germane to the hydrogen economy.
In this country, we can deliver

00:14:48.330 --> 00:14:52.110
energy through the electric grid,
and we can deliver gas through gas

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.850
pipelines.
You cannot send hydrogen through the

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:59.570
gas pipelines because the gas
pipelines are stable with

00:14:59.570 --> 00:15:03.280
hydrocarbon contents,
but not stable with hydrogen.

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:06.990
Hydrogen under pressure will
embrittle those pipelines.

00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:10.710
That means that we would have to
build a new infrastructure to pipe

00:15:10.710 --> 00:15:14.420
hydrogen over long distances.
And, that infrastructure cannot be

00:15:14.420 --> 00:15:18.140
made out of steel because steel will
be embrittled. It's not

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:21.880
going to be cheap.
These are cost issues.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:25.660
You need to know this because
people are going to ask you.

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:29.440
You're from MIT. They're going to
ask you help make policy.

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:33.220
You can't just get on board and say,
well, we'll fix it somehow.

00:15:33.220 --> 00:15:36.990
Hydrogen is very small. It goes
places where it's not supposed to be.

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:40.770
OK, then the third type of defect
